# README for wsl instance using ddns --
# these files are needed to support a ddns client running in a Windows Subsystem for Linux (WSL) instance of joetoo
#   prerequisites - installed WSL instance ("distribution") joetoo-nat
#   move the .ps1 files to C:\Scripts\ or /mnt/c/Scripts/ (same place)
#   and create a windows terminal taskbar icon profile for joetoo-nat
#   - put terminal on taskbar if not already ther
#   - open a terminal as administrator and click the "v" to the right of the tab at the top
#   - click settings
#   - right-click the joetoo-nat line (bottom left)
#   - click into the command line panel and enter the following command line --
#        powershell.exe -ExecutionPolicy Bypass -File C:\scripts\launch-joetoo_nat.ps1
#   - save
# then right-click terminal and select joetoo-nat to spin up the instance
#   note that  C:\scripts\launch-joetoo_nat.ps1 calls C:\scripts\wsl_netsh_prep.ps1
#   to run a scheduled task to set up portproxy rules with elevated privilegs
#   (this forwards both ipv4 and ipv6 traffic to the host on port 2222 to the
#    nat'd ipv4 address on the WSL instance - so bidirectional ssh works)
# ddns-daemon can install under openrc, but it can't access the host ip address
#   so it won't work.  Instead, run install /etc/local.d/99-ddns-wsl-host-proxy.start
#   and chmod +x to trigger a ddns update on boot.  Also set up /etc/cron.d/ddns-trigger-wsl.crontab
#   to trigger ddns-update every 5 minutes and let the latter's cache management
#   determine if any update is needed
#
# instuctions for ebuild -

# ddns-trigger-wsl.crontab ......: install to /etc/cron.d/ .........: cron job to trigger ea 5 min
# ddns-trigger-wsl* .............: install to /usr/sbin/ ...........: ipv4 and ipv6 trigger scripts
#                                                                   : called by .start and cron
# 99-ddns-wsl-host-proxy.start ..: install to /etc/local.d/ ........: .start file (ddns-update on boot)
# resolvconf.conf.wsl ...........: install to /resolvconf.conf .....: WSL-specific version to set up resolv.conf
# wsl.conf ......................: install to /etc/ ................: [boot] starts openrc; plus [network] & [user]
# .wslconfig* ...................: install to /mnt/c/Users/joebr/ ..: Windows User config - [wsl2] sets networkingMode=nat
# *.ps1 .........................: install to /mnt/c/Scripts/ ......: Powershell scripts to set up and launch a WSL instance
